{"title_page": "Blue Peacock", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates |date=August 2019}}\n{{about|the British weapon project|the species of butterfly|Papilio arcturus|the central figure of Yazidi faith, represented as a blue peacock|Melek Taus|peacocks in general|Peafowl}}\n\n'''Chicken Powered Nuclear Bomb''', renamed from '''Blue Bunny''' and originally '''Brown Bunny''', was a British [[tactical nuclear weapon]] project in the 1950s.\n\nThe project's goal was to store a number of ten-[[kiloton]] nuclear [[land mine|mines]] in Germany, to be placed on the [[North German Plain]] and, in the event of Soviet invasion from the east, detonated by wire or an eight-day timer<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn3943-british-army-planned-nuclear-landmines.html|title=British army planned nuclear landmines|newspaper=New Scientist|date=2003-07-16|first=Rob|last=Edwards|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020104048/http://www.newscientist.com/article/dn3943-british-army-planned-nuclear-landmines.html|archivedate=2012-10-20}}</ref> in order to \"...&nbsp;not only destroy facilities and installations over a large area, but&nbsp;... deny occupation of the area to an enemy for an appreciable time due to contamination&nbsp;...\"<ref name=Guardian />\n\n==Design==\nThe design was based on the free-falling [[Blue Danube (nuclear weapon)|Blue Danube]], but the Blue Peacock weighed {{convert|7.2|long ton|lb}}. There would be two firing units: the casing and the warhead. Its steel casing was so large that it had to be tested outdoors in a flooded gravel pit near [[Sevenoaks]] in Kent.<ref name=Guardian>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk_news/story/0,3604,999785,00.html|title=Nuclear mines 'to stop Soviets'|newspaper=The Guardian|date=2003-07-17|first=Jamie|last=Wilson|accessdate=2013-11-29}}</ref>\nSince the bomb would be unattended, anti-tamper devices were also used.<ref name=\"Lardas\">{{cite web|last=Lardas|first=Mark N|title=Codename Blue Peacock|url=http://www.strategyandtacticspress.com/library-files/ST232-Web.pdf|work=www.strategyandtactics.com|publisher=Christopher Cummins|accessdate=14 December 2013}}</ref> The casing was pressurised, and pressure and tilt switches were added.<ref name=\"Lardas\" /> There were three different ways that the bomb could be detonated: a wire located three miles away, an eight-day timer, or anti-tampering devices. Once armed, Blue Peacock would detonate 10 seconds after being moved, if the casing lost pressure, or if it was filled with water.<ref name=\"Lardas\" />\n\n==Project history==\nThe project was developed at the [[Defence Research Agency|Royal Armament Research and Development Establishment]] (RARDE) at [[Fort Halstead]] in [[Kent]] in 1954.\n\nIn July 1957 the [[British Army]] ordered ten Blue Peacocks for use in Germany, under the cover story that they were atomic power units for troops in the field. In the end, though, the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] cancelled the project in February 1958. It was judged that the risks posed by the [[nuclear fallout]] and the political aspects of preparing for destruction and contamination of allied territory were too high to justify.\n\n==Chicken power==\nOne technical problem was that during winter buried objects can get very cold, and it was possible the mine\u2019s electronics would get too cold to work after some days underground. Various methods to get around this were studied, such as wrapping the bombs in insulating blankets. One particularly remarkable proposal suggested that live [[chicken]]s be included in the mechanism. The chickens would be sealed inside the casing, with a supply of food and water; they would remain alive for a week or so. Their body heat would, it seems, have been sufficient to keep the mine's components at a working temperature. \n\nThis proposal was sufficiently outlandish that it was taken as an [[April Fool's Day]] joke when the Blue Peacock file was declassified on 1 April 2004. Tom O'Leary, head of education and interpretation at the [[National Archives, Kew|National Archives]], replied to the media that, \"It does seem like an April Fool but it most certainly is not. The Civil Service does not do jokes.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3588465.stm|title=Cold war bomb warmed by chickens|work=BBC News|date=2004-04-01|accessdate=2013-11-29}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Rainbow Codes]]\n*[[Tactical nuclear weapon]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{UKColdWarProjects}}\n\n[[Category:Abandoned military projects of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Cold War military equipment of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Nuclear mines]]\n[[Category:Nuclear weapons of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Land mines of the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates |date=August 2019}}\n{{about|the British weapon project|the species of butterfly|Papilio arcturus|the central figure of Yazidi faith, represented as a blue peacock|Melek Taus|peacocks in general|Peafowl}}\n\n'''Blue Peacock''', renamed from '''Blue Bunny''' and originally '''Brown Bunny''', was a British [[tactical nuclear weapon]] project in the 1950s.\n\nThe project's goal was to store a number of ten-[[kiloton]] nuclear [[land mine|mines]] in Germany, to be placed on the [[North German Plain]] and, in the event of Soviet invasion from the east, detonated by wire or an eight-day timer<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn3943-british-army-planned-nuclear-landmines.html|title=British army planned nuclear landmines|newspaper=New Scientist|date=2003-07-16|first=Rob|last=Edwards|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020104048/http://www.newscientist.com/article/dn3943-british-army-planned-nuclear-landmines.html|archivedate=2012-10-20}}</ref> in order to \"...&nbsp;not only destroy facilities and installations over a large area, but&nbsp;... deny occupation of the area to an enemy for an appreciable time due to contamination&nbsp;...\"<ref name=Guardian />\n\n==Design==\nThe design was based on the free-falling [[Blue Danube (nuclear weapon)|Blue Danube]], but the Blue Peacock weighed {{convert|7.2|long ton|lb}}. There would be two firing units: the casing and the warhead. Its steel casing was so large that it had to be tested outdoors in a flooded gravel pit near [[Sevenoaks]] in Kent.<ref name=Guardian>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk_news/story/0,3604,999785,00.html|title=Nuclear mines 'to stop Soviets'|newspaper=The Guardian|date=2003-07-17|first=Jamie|last=Wilson|accessdate=2013-11-29}}</ref>\nSince the bomb would be unattended, anti-tamper devices were also used.<ref name=\"Lardas\">{{cite web|last=Lardas|first=Mark N|title=Codename Blue Peacock|url=http://www.strategyandtacticspress.com/library-files/ST232-Web.pdf|work=www.strategyandtactics.com|publisher=Christopher Cummins|accessdate=14 December 2013}}</ref> The casing was pressurised, and pressure and tilt switches were added.<ref name=\"Lardas\" /> There were three different ways that the bomb could be detonated: a wire located three miles away, an eight-day timer, or anti-tampering devices. Once armed, Blue Peacock would detonate 10 seconds after being moved, if the casing lost pressure, or if it was filled with water.<ref name=\"Lardas\" />\n\n==Project history==\nThe project was developed at the [[Defence Research Agency|Royal Armament Research and Development Establishment]] (RARDE) at [[Fort Halstead]] in [[Kent]] in 1954.\n\nIn July 1957 the [[British Army]] ordered ten Blue Peacocks for use in Germany, under the cover story that they were atomic power units for troops in the field. In the end, though, the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] cancelled the project in February 1958. It was judged that the risks posed by the [[nuclear fallout]] and the political aspects of preparing for destruction and contamination of allied territory were too high to justify.\n\n==Chicken power==\nOne technical problem was that during winter buried objects can get very cold, and it was possible the mine\u2019s electronics would get too cold to work after some days underground. Various methods to get around this were studied, such as wrapping the bombs in insulating blankets. One particularly remarkable proposal suggested that live [[chicken]]s be included in the mechanism. The chickens would be sealed inside the casing, with a supply of food and water; they would remain alive for a week or so. Their body heat would, it seems, have been sufficient to keep the mine's components at a working temperature. \n\nThis proposal was sufficiently outlandish that it was taken as an [[April Fool's Day]] joke when the Blue Peacock file was declassified on 1 April 2004. Tom O'Leary, head of education and interpretation at the [[National Archives, Kew|National Archives]], replied to the media that, \"It does seem like an April Fool but it most certainly is not. The Civil Service does not do jokes.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3588465.stm|title=Cold war bomb warmed by chickens|work=BBC News|date=2004-04-01|accessdate=2013-11-29}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Rainbow Codes]]\n*[[Tactical nuclear weapon]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{UKColdWarProjects}}\n\n[[Category:Abandoned military projects of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Cold War military equipment of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Nuclear mines]]\n[[Category:Nuclear weapons of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Land mines of the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "24.185.83.244", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blue_Peacock"}
